english:
  title: A Farewell Sequence for Minister of Works Sung Kong-im Upon His Departure to the Capital
  author: Kim Su-on
  language: eng
  text: "I have read the words of Mencius, which say: \"To recite his poems and read his writings without knowing the man—can this suffice? Thus we must consider his age.\" In truth, among the ancient kings, who surpassed Yao, Shun, Yu, and Tang? Yet their traces lie distant and unseen. Among the sages of old, who exceeded Confucius, Yan Hui, Zi Si, and Mencius? Yet their dwelling places remain far and inaccessible. \n\nThough we study the Two Canons and Three Counsels until their meanings shine clear, though we master the Analects, Mencius, Doctrine of the Mean, and Great Learning until our recitation flows smooth—is this not like one who laughs toward the east while Chang'an lies to the west? Is this not like the wheelwright who clutches his chisel and smirks in secret? Must we not sigh deeply at such hollow learning, we who love antiquity and seek truth?\n\nMinister Sung possesses keen brilliance and vast understanding, learning that illuminates principle and serves the practical world. Twice victorious in the highest examinations, he has come to his moment and shown his worth, rising to become a renowned minister. Now bearing the mandate of a tributary state to the Son of Heaven's court, he gazes southward upon the mountains of Zou and Lu, hears the waters of the Zhu and Si murmur their ancient song—verdant and flowing, they stir in him the echoes of a thousand ages. Northward, he approaches the imperial capital, the very city of Ji Province spoken of in Yu's tribute, where Yao, Shun, Yu, and Tang once held their courts. There the customs flow with harmony and peace, with gentle prosperity. Thus he does more than merely recite the classics—he treads their sacred ground. What he gains from such witnessing transcends all words. How vastly different is this from one who speaks of ancient ages without knowing the men who shaped them!\n\nMoreover, our Great Ming possesses sacred virtue and divine achievement that tower above all sovereigns of old. It has unified all under heaven, both near and far shores bending to its rule, extending east and west to the very limits of creation. Though I cannot behold Tang and Yu of old, why should I not observe the governance of Great Ming? The governance of Great Ming is none other than the governance of the Two Emperors and Three Kings. Though I cannot see Confucius and Mencius, why should I not witness the splendor of Great Ming's culture and teaching? The culture and teaching of Great Ming embody none other than the Way of Confucius and Mencius.\n\nWhy toil to discourse upon distant ages and seek their governance in centuries past, when one may directly perceive it in the present? Why strain to commune with ancient sages across the gulf of ages, when one may stand in their very presence today? \n\nShould Minister Sung truly observe the rites, music, and cultural refinement of the imperial court, comparing them with what the classics reveal of root and branch, substance and form, he will discern what belongs to antiquity and what to the present. Observing how the court nurtures talent through education, he will measure it against the profound teachings of Confucius and Mencius on broadening learning and restraining conduct through ritual. In all things, reconciling the universal with the particular, grasping the mean, he will return such wisdom to himself—his learning deepened—and extend it to the state—his governance perfected.\n\nYet there are those who gaze upon mountains, rivers, and walled cities, thinking merely of ancient regions—of Qi and Lu, of Ji and Yong provinces—who know that Yao dwelt at Yi Gorge and Shun at Pu Bank, who recognize Que Li as Confucius's home and Ping Lu as Mencius's seat, and who declare: \"I have already witnessed the traces of kings and sages—why need I further know these men or examine their ages?\" Such a one speaks with shallow understanding. Would Minister Sung adopt such a view?\n\nWhen at last he has presented his memorial and received the imperial favor to return, bringing honor to our lord's devotion to the greater realm, then I shall rejoice twofold: above, that the state has gained a worthy minister whose virtue perfects its governance; below, that our Way bears real fruit in the cultivation of the self and the transformation of others."
  footnotes:
    - The Two Canons refer to the Yijing and Shangshu; the Three Counsels refer to sections of classical texts containing royal guidance.
    - The allusion to Chang'an and the wheelwright derives from a Zhuangzi parable about the gap between theory and true understanding.
    - Zou and Lu were the regions of Mencius and Confucius respectively; the Zhu and Si rivers flow through lands sacred to Confucian tradition.
    - The Two Emperors are typically Yao and Shun; the Three Kings are Yu, Tang, and either Wen or Zhou.
    - This essay, while taking the form of a farewell for Minister Sung's journey to the Ming court, serves as a meditation on how direct encounter with exemplary governance surpasses mere study of ancient texts.
